Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

# Plot Histogram + Boxplot (Mortgage)

# Define the histogram + boxplot function
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the dataset
    - feature: Column name to be visualized
    - figsize: Figure size (default: (12,7))
    - kde: Whether to show the density curve (default: False)
    - bins: Number of bins for histogram (default: None)
    """
    # Create figure with 2 subplots (boxplot + histogram)
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Two subplots (boxplot and histogram)
        sharex=True,  # Share x-axis
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},  # Boxplot takes 25% height, histogram 75%
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # Create boxplot on the top subplot
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )

    # Create histogram on the bottom subplot
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )

    # Add vertical lines for mean and median
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--", label="Mean"
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-", label="Median"
    )

    # Add legend to histogram
    ax_hist2.legend()

    # Show the plots
    plt.show()

# Generate the histogram + boxplot for the "Mortgage" column
histogram_boxplot(data=df, feature="Mortgage", kde=True, bins=30)
  • Observations:

-- The mortgage data seems to be positive or right skewed due to the mean value being to the right of the median as indicated above in the green and black lines in the histogram chart.

-- A large number of customers do not have a mortgage as indicated by spike at 0 on the barchart above. This indicates a large number of customers might be renters instead of homeowners. I can further analyze age to mortgage to get a better indication of that assumption.

-- The data is right skewed indicating that a large number of customers have lower mortgage values. There are a few outliers with higher mortgages.

# Plot Histogram + Boxplot (Income)

# Define the histogram + boxplot function
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the dataset
    - feature: Column name to be visualized
    - figsize: Figure size (default: (12,7))
    - kde: Whether to show the density curve (default: False)
    - bins: Number of bins for histogram (default: None)
    """
    # Create figure with 2 subplots (boxplot + histogram)
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Two subplots (boxplot and histogram)
        sharex=True,  # Share x-axis
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},  # Boxplot takes 25% height, histogram 75%
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # Calculate percentiles
    q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    q2 = data[feature].quantile(0.50)  # Median
    q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)

    # Create boxplot on the top subplot
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )

    # Label percentiles on the boxplot
    ax_box2.text(q1, 0, "25%", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="blue")
    ax_box2.text(q2, 0, "50% (Median)", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="black")
    ax_box2.text(q3, 0, "75%", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="blue")

    # Create histogram on the bottom subplot
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )

    # Add vertical lines for mean and median
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--", label="Mean"
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-", label="Median"
    )

    # Add legend to histogram
    ax_hist2.legend()

    # Show the plots
    plt.show()

# Generate the histogram + boxplot for the "Mortgage" column
histogram_boxplot(data=df, feature="Income", kde=True, bins=30)
  • Observations:

-- The Income distribution is right skewed because the Mean is larger than the Median as indicated by the dashed green line to the right of the straight black line.

-- The income shows a wide range from 8K to 224K. This is further observed by gthe large standard deviation of 46K.

-- The interquartile range (IQR) is from 39K to 98K, meaning most customers earn within this range.

-- The boxplot shows a large number of outliers above gthe upper whisker.

-- The median income is $64K, meaning half of the customers earn below this value and half the customers earn abovwe this value.

    - bins: Number of bins for histogram (default: None)
    """

        nrows=2,  # Two subplots (boxplot and histogram)
        sharex=True,  # Share x-axis
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},  # Boxplot takes 25% height, histogram 75%
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # Calculate percentiles
    q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    q2 = data[feature].quantile(0.50)  # Median
    q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)

    # Create boxplot on the top subplot
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )

    # Label percentiles on the boxplot

# Plot Histogram + Boxplot (Experience)
# Years of professional experience

# Define the histogram + boxplot function
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the dataset
    - feature: Column name to be visualized
    - figsize: Figure size (default: (12,7))
    - kde: Whether to show the density curve (default: False)
    - bins: Number of bins for histogram (default: None)
    """
    # Create figure with 2 subplots (boxplot + histogram)
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Two subplots (boxplot and histogram)
        sharex=True,  # Share x-axis
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},  # Boxplot takes 25% height, histogram 75%
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # Calculate percentiles
    q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
    q2 = data[feature].quantile(0.50)  # Median
    q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)

    # Create boxplot on the top subplot
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )

    # Label percentiles on the boxplot
    ax_box2.text(q1, 0, "25%", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="blue")
    ax_box2.text(q2, 0, "50% (Median)", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="black")
    ax_box2.text(q3, 0, "75%", ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10, color="blue")

    # Create histogram on the bottom subplot
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )

    # Add vertical lines for mean and median
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--", label="Mean"
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-", label="Median"
    )

    # Add legend to histogram
    ax_hist2.legend()

    # Show the plots
    plt.show()

# Univariate Analysis for Categorical data: (Education, Personal_Loan, Securities_Account, CD_Account, Online, CreditCard, and Family)
# Create Barchart for Education

# Define function to create bar charts with custom labels for categorical features
def plot_bar_chart_with_labels(data, feature, title=None, labels=None):
    """
    Function to plot a bar chart for categorical features with custom labels.

    Parameters:
    - data: DataFrame containing the dataset
    - feature: Column name (categorical feature) to visualize
    - title: Custom title for the plot (default: None)
    - labels: Dictionary mapping feature values to custom labels (default: None)
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))

    # Create a bar chart
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=feature, palette="coolwarm")

    # Set title and labels
    plt.title(title if title else f"Distribution of {feature}", fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(feature, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=12)

    # Set custom labels if provided
    if labels:
        ax.set_xticklabels([labels[val] for val in sorted(data[feature].unique())])

    # Show value counts on bars
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(f'{int(p.get_height())}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                    ha='center', va='baseline', fontsize=12, color='black', xytext=(0, 5),
                    textcoords='offset points')

    plt.show()

# Define custom labels for Education levels
education_labels = {1: "Undergrad", 2: "Graduate", 3: "Advanced/Professional"}

# Generate bar chart for Education with custom labels
plot_bar_chart_with_labels(data, "Education", "Distribution of Education Levels", labels=education_labels)

# Display value counts in ascending order
data["Education"].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=True)

Univariate Analysis Summary:¶

Numerical Features (Histograms + Boxplots)

-- Income → Right-skewed, wide variation, potential outliers.

-- CCAvg (Credit Card Spending) → Right-skewed, few high spenders.

-- Mortgage → Most customers have no mortgage, some outliers.

-- Experience → Fairly even distribution.

-- Age → Evenly distributed, no major outliers.

Categorical Features (Bar Charts)

-- Education → Mostly Undergrad & Graduate levels.

-- Personal Loan → Very low acceptance rate, potential class imbalance.

-- CD Account & Securities Account → Low ownership.

-- Online Banking → Majority use online banking.

-- CreditCard (Other Banks) → 71% do not have an external credit card.

-- Family Size → Most customers have 2 to 4+ members.

In [75]:
# Step 1: Compute Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
Q1 = data.select_dtypes(include=["float64", "int64"]).quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data.select_dtypes(include=["float64", "int64"]).quantile(0.75)

# Step 2: Compute Interquartile Range (IQR)
IQR = Q3 - Q1  # Measures the spread of the middle 50% of the data

# Step 3: Compute Lower and Upper Bound for Outliers
lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR  # Lower bound for outliers
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR  # Upper bound for outliers

Model Building and Performance Improvement¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

  • For this business case objective of trying to expand the bank's loan business and market to those individuals it feels would likely accept a loan offer, I'm going to move forward with reducing false negatives and use Recall as my model evaluation criteria.

  • This:

-- Minimizes False Negatives (FN) → Ensures that qualified potential loan customers aren’t mistakenly rejected.

-- Maximizes Customer Reach → Helps identify as many loan-eligible customers as possible.

-- Supports Business Growth → Focuses on capturing more customers rather than just avoiding bad approvals as would potentially be the case if I used Precision as my model evaulation criteria.

-- I considered using F1 to strike a balance between Recall and Precision, however I am going to use Recall as my final model evaluation criteria.

-- The company would want the recall to be maximized, the greater the recall score is, the higher are the chances of minimizing the False Negatives.

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

-- The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.

-- The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot confusion matrix.

In [102]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [103]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Decision Tree (Pre-pruning)¶

  • Note - I removed the class_weight="balanced" because I was getting way too many errors and false positives due to over-compensation. Re-running all models without this parameter again.

  • Hyperparameter tuning plays a critical role in optimizing model performance.

  • Unlike model parameters, which are learned during training, hyperparameters must be set beforehand. Proper tuning enhances both the accuracy and robustness of the model.

  • The loop below systematically iterates through predefined hyperparameter values to identify the optimal model based on the chosen evaluation metric, specifically the recall score.

In [161]:
# Define the parameters of the tree to iterate over
max_depth_values = np.arange(2, 7, 2) # [2, 4, 6] Training 48 trees
max_leaf_nodes_values = [50, 75, 150, 250]
min_samples_split_values = [10, 30, 50, 70]

# Initialize variables to store the best model and its performance
best_estimator = None
best_score_diff = float('inf')
best_test_score = 0.0

# Iterate over all combinations of the specified parameter values
for max_depth in max_depth_values:
    for max_leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
        for min_samples_split in min_samples_split_values:

            # Initialize the tree with the current set of parameters
            estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                max_depth=max_depth,
                max_leaf_nodes=max_leaf_nodes,
                min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
                random_state=42
            )

            # Fit the model to the training data
            estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

            # Make predictions on the training and test sets
            y_train_pred = estimator.predict(X_train)
            y_test_pred = estimator.predict(X_test)

            # Calculate recall scores for training and test sets
            train_recall_score = recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
            test_recall_score = recall_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

            # Calculate the absolute difference between training and test recall scores
            score_diff = abs(train_recall_score - test_recall_score)

            # OLD
            # Update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference
            # if (score_diff < best_score_diff) & (test_recall_score > best_test_score):
            #  best_score_diff = score_diff
            #  best_test_score = test_recall_score
            #  best_estimator = estimator

            # NEW - Note* - made no difference from the old code above. I got the same Decision Tree depth.
            # Update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference

            # Based on feedback, removed the *(score_diff < best_score_diff)* Statement for best Recall value between train and test.
            if test_recall_score > best_test_score:
                best_score_diff = score_diff
                best_test_score = test_recall_score
                best_estimator = estimator

# Print the best parameters
print("Best parameters found:")
print(f"Max depth: {best_estimator.max_depth}")
print(f"Max leaf nodes: {best_estimator.max_leaf_nodes}")
print(f"Min samples split: {best_estimator.min_samples_split}")
print(f"Best test recall score: {best_test_score}")

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  • Observations, Recommendations, and Key Insights:

  • The model built can be used to predict whether or not a bank customer will accept a personal loan offer through AllLife Bank.

  • Income level, Average Credit Card Spend/Balance, Education Level, and lastly Family Size are the most important variables in predicting whether an AllLife Bank customer will accept a personal loan offer.

  • This model is expected to correctly predict the above 98.6% of the time.

1️⃣ High-Income Customers Are More Likely to Accept Loans

  • Observation: Our models indicate a strong correlation between income level and loan acceptance.

  • Recommendation:

  • Target high-income individuals with personalized loan offers.

2️⃣ Customers with Higher Credit Card Spending Tend to Accept Loans

  • Observation: CCAvg (Credit Card Average Spending) is a strong indicator of loan acceptance.

  • Recommendation:

  • Identify high-spending credit card users and offer pre-approved loans.

3️⃣ Education Level Affects Loan Acceptance

  • Observation: Customers with higher education levels (Graduate & Advanced degrees) are more likely to accept loans.

  • Recommendation:

  • Prioritize targeted marketing for professionals with graduate and postgraduate degrees.

4️⃣ Large Family Size Increases Loan Acceptance

  • Observation: Customers with larger families (3-4 members) tend to accept loans more frequently.

  • Recommendation:

  • Introduce family-focused loan programs, such as education loans, home renovation loans, or vacation financing.

  • Create targeted email & digital campaigns for customers with families.

5️⃣ Online Banking Users Are More Receptive to Loan Offers

  • Observation: Customers who actively use online banking have a higher loan acceptance rate.

  • Recommendation:

  • Leverage digital marketing & push notifications to promote loans to active online banking users.

  • Simplify the loan application process via the online banking portal for quick approvals.
